labels.en: Immersed Tunnel Ontology - Site and Environmental Systems

comments.en:
Site characterization and environmental systems module for immersed tunnel engineering aligned with GBT 51318-2019.
            Defines comprehensive framework for site investigation, environmental assessment, and monitoring systems.
            
            STANDARDS ALIGNMENT:
            - GBT 51318-2019 Chapter 4: Engineering Survey and Site Investigation methodology
            - Section 4.3: Phased tunnel investigation framework and requirements
            - Section 4.2.2: Comprehensive survey data type specifications
            - Investigation phases: feasibility study, preliminary, detailed, and supplemental
            
            INVESTIGATION FRAMEWORK:
            - Phased investigation approach matching design stages
            - Subaqueous topographic mapping with scale-specific requirements
            - Water area investigation with systematic borehole arrangements
            - Hydrological investigation including flow velocity and water characteristics
            - Integration of underwater and terrestrial survey methodologies
            
            MODULE SCOPE:
            - Site investigation classification and methodology framework
            - Environmental assessment and monitoring system taxonomy
            - Survey data type definitions aligned with standard requirements
            - Environmental protection and sustainability system architecture
            - Design parameter derivation from investigation data

comment.en: Energy efficiency measures for sustainable tunnel operation.
Comprehensive geometric design framework for tunnel plan layout, profile design, and dimensional specifications.
Systematic monitoring of water current patterns and flow characteristics for construction planning and structural loading analysis.
Location assessment based on seismic activity and engineering geological conditions with mitigation measures for unsuitable zones.
Noise control measures for construction and operational activities.
Systematic framework for controlled technical schemes including dry dock, connection segments, floating transportation, and immersion methods.
Air quality control measures including emissions reduction.
Meteorological monitoring system for construction scheduling and safety planning based on weather condition forecasting.
3D models of the seafloor for geometric boundary definition.
Borehole investigation in soft soil conditions with depth requirements based on tunnel height multiples and minimum depth specifications.

Main structural concrete specification for immersed tunnel elements adopting waterproof concrete with impermeability grade not lower than P8 as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 6.0.2. Minimum strength grade shall not be lower than C35 per Section 6.0.4. Raw materials and mix proportions must meet durability requirements including minimum strength, maximum water-cement ratio, minimum cementitious material content, and requirements for crack resistance, impermeability, freeze-thaw resistance, and corrosion resistance.
High-strength low-relaxation steel strand specification for PC tendons with minimum ultimate strength 1860 MPa.
Extended mapping coverage including element floating transportation area when utilizing movable dry dock construction methodology.
GINA and OMEGA waterstop specification with associated pressure plates and steel components meeting durability requirements.
Waste management and disposal systems for construction and operation.
Comprehensive environmental baseline studies and impact assessment for regulatory compliance and sustainable development.
Monitoring of seabed changes, sediment transport, and scour development around tunnel structures for long-term stability assessment.
Systematic underwater topographic survey and bathymetric mapping for accurate spatial definition of construction environment.

Initial phase investigation conducted based on data collection and site visits as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.3.3. Includes borehole spacing of 400-500m with minimum 2 boreholes and at least one borehole per construction unit or tunnel alignment section. Provides essential data for project viability assessment and preliminary site reconnaissance.
Design framework for element length, number, and cross-sectional dimensions based on fabrication, floating, immersion, and structural requirements.
Detailed topographic mapping for construction documentation with scale range 1:500 to 1:1000 and coverage extending 0.5-1 km on both sides of tunnel alignment.
Micro-expansive concrete specification for backfill behind elements with impermeability and strength not lower than main structural concrete.
Constraints for structural design based on site conditions and loading requirements.
Comprehensive framework for site characterization, investigation, and survey methodologies supporting tunnel design and construction planning.
Specialized material specification framework including grouting materials, prestressing tendons, waterstops, and support components.
Load-bearing capacity, permeability, and settlement potential data for foundation design.
Investigation of water flow velocity patterns and variations affecting construction planning and structural design considerations.
Borehole investigation in slightly or moderately weathered rock formations with specific depth requirements and cavity penetration protocols.

Systematic framework for tunnel location selection considering geological hazards, seismic activity, hydrological conditions, and environmental factors as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 5.2. Must avoid dangerous zones such as landslides, mudslides, and seismic fault fracture zones. Preferably located in hydrologically and morphologically stable, flat riverbed sections where maximum depth does not exceed 50m and flow velocity meets operational requirements for floating and immersion.
Investigation of water density characteristics affecting buoyancy calculations and element flotation design parameters.
Assessment of atmospheric conditions and air quality parameters affecting tunnel ventilation design and operational requirements.
Comprehensive design framework encompassing tunnel alignment, profile, cross-section, elevation, and element floating and immersion design considerations.
Continuous monitoring of water level variations and tidal fluctuations affecting tunnel structural design and construction operations.
Assessment of impacts on marine environment and ecosystems.
Constraints for geotechnical design based on soil properties and foundation requirements.
Geological investigation data including stratum lithology and physical properties for IMMTD02 research data exchange.
Elevation design framework ensuring positioning below planned navigation channel depth with adequate protective cover over tunnel roof.

Prestressed concrete specification for immersed tunnel element sections with minimum strength grade not lower than C40 as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 6.0.4. Must meet enhanced durability requirements and structural performance criteria for prestressed construction applications in underwater environment.
Design framework for drainage pump stations at tunnel entrances and lowest points meeting transportation functional requirements.
Renewable energy systems integration for sustainable operations.
Comprehensive investigation of water area hydrological characteristics including flow velocity, water level, density, and related parameters affecting tunnel design and construction.
Investigation within element floating zones requiring trenching, with borehole arrangement based on regional geology and construction calculation requirements.
Design framework for tunnel internal clearance meeting architectural, equipment, construction tolerance, and deformation requirements.
Alignment design framework complying with planning requirements and coordinating relationships with surrounding buildings, navigation, and underground infrastructure.
Anti-corrosion concrete layer specification with minimum strength grade C20 for protective applications.
Assessment framework for hydrologically and morphologically stable riverbed sections with maximum depth constraints and flow velocity requirements.
Initial borehole investigation with 400-500m spacing, minimum 2 boreholes, and depth requirements based on soil conditions and tunnel dimensions.
Comprehensive borehole investigation using staggered grid arrangement with specific spacing for joint-affected areas (30-50m) and excavation slopes (40-60m).
Systematic assessment of water quality characteristics and chemical composition affecting construction materials and operational environment.

Systematic engineering survey and site investigation framework conducted according to technical features, design requirements, and regional conditions of immersed tunnels as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.3.1. Investigation phases match design stages and ensure accurate and reliable data collection with precision complying with relevant national standards.
Systematic evaluation of ambient noise levels and acoustic impact assessment for construction and operational phases.
Topographic mapping during feasibility study based on data collection and site surveys, with precision meeting regulatory approval requirements.
Parameters defining conditions for trench stability during excavation and construction.

Meteorological data including temperature, humidity, rainfall, fog, wind direction, and wind speed parameters. Critical for construction scheduling, safety planning, and operational design considerations as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.2.2.

Environmental data including atmospheric environment near the tunnel alignment, vehicle exhaust emissions, noise requirements, ecological protection requirements, and surrounding external environmental conditions. Essential for environmental impact assessment and regulatory compliance as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.2.2.

Hydrological and geological data including water level, wave conditions, flow velocity, flow direction, water temperature, water depth, water quality, flood protection standards, river regulation, and river-sea regime changes. Fundamental for hydraulic design and environmental impact assessment as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.2.2.
Connection segment scheme at tunnel ends matching dry dock scheme and prefabrication schedule requirements.

label.en: Along-the-Line Surface and Underground Construction Data

comment.en: Along-the-line surface and underground construction data including buildings, structures, pipelines, cultural relics, military facilities, mineral resources, and hazardous explosive items. Critical for construction safety, risk assessment, and regulatory compliance as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.2.2.
Intermediate borehole investigation with 100-300m spacing, minimum 5 boreholes in complex areas, with general and control borehole depth specifications.
Systematic underwater investigation methodology with phase-specific borehole spacing and depth requirements for comprehensive subsurface characterization.
Systematic monitoring framework for environmental conditions and parameters affecting tunnel design, construction, and operational performance.

Reinforcement steel specification with main reinforcement bars using HRB400 or HRB500 grades and stirrups using HPB300 or HRB400 grades as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 6.0.8. Ensures adequate structural reinforcement performance in immersed tunnel concrete elements.
Specialized investigation for river or sea bottoms covered by silt, including thickness measurement and sediment density determination.
Groundwater levels, flow rates, and interaction with tunnel structure for hydraulic design.
Floating transportation method determination based on dock type, navigation conditions, floating distance, hydrology, and meteorological factors.
Water quality protection measures during construction and operation.
Soil and rock composition data of the construction area for design analysis.

Comprehensive investigation phase providing precise site data for final design development and construction documentation as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.3.3. Utilizes staggered grid arrangement with 30-50m spacing in joint-affected areas and 40-60m spacing on excavation slopes. Essential for construction drawing design stage requirements.
Additional investigation conducted as necessary to address specific design requirements or resolve identified uncertainties.

Structural steel specification for immersed tunnel element end walls, watertight doors, shear keys, and end closure components using Q235B grade as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 6.0.7. Ensures structural integrity and waterproofing performance in underwater construction applications.
Systematic drilling investigation for subsurface exploration with phase-specific spacing, depth, and arrangement requirements.
Cross-sectional design framework meeting tunnel clearance, structural stress, deformation, and buoyancy design requirements.
Assessment of ecological systems, biodiversity impacts, and environmental protection requirements for sustainable construction practices.
Lifecycle environmental impact assessment for sustainable design.
Sediment control measures to minimize turbidity and deposition.
Design parameters for tunnel joint performance and waterproofing systems.
Element immersion method determination based on navigation conditions, hydrological environment, element structure, and construction equipment.

Engineering geology and seismic data including topography, geology, engineering geology, regional seismic activity, seismic intensity for protection, seismic zoning for design, and basic seismic acceleration for design. Essential for structural design and seismic risk assessment as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.2.2.
Final joint location and structural form determination based on navigation conditions, tunnel depth, dry dock scheme, and construction schedule.

Base class for survey data types systematically categorized according to GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.2.2 comprehensive survey content requirements. Encompasses all data collection categories essential for informed design and construction decision-making.
Concrete specification framework including waterproof concrete requirements, impermeability grades, durability requirements, and strength classifications.
Alignment design for immersed element sections with preference for straight alignment or curvature based on functional and construction requirements.

Comprehensive materials specification framework based on structural type, load conditions, usage requirements, and environmental factors as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 6.0.1. Ensures selection of engineering materials meets safety, reliability, technical advancement, economic reasonableness, and durability principles established in the standard's general provisions.
Assessment of impacts on land-based environment and communities.
Longitudinal profile design framework based on topography, geology, and engineering construction conditions meeting long-term planning requirements.
Sustainable development and green construction practices.
Assessment of cumulative environmental impacts from multiple projects.
Severe environment with high aggressive conditions.
Aggressive environment requiring enhanced protection.
Moderate environment with some aggressive conditions.
Ordinary environment with minimal aggressive conditions.
Non-shrink grouting material specification for element end sealing injection with minimum strength grade M25.
Environmental protection measures and mitigation strategies.
Environmental category classification per JTG/T 3371-2022 and GB/T 50476.
Stratification profiles from borehole investigations for subsurface characterization.
Ballast tank concrete specification with minimum design strength grade C25 for structural applications.
Comprehensive environmental impact assessment for tunnel projects.
Assessment framework for avoiding dangerous zones including landslides, mudslides, and seismic fault fracture zones.

Systematic underwater topographic survey methodology ensuring seamless integration of underwater and terrestrial measurements as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.3.2. Scale requirements vary by design stage: feasibility study based on data collection meeting regulatory approval precision, preliminary design at 1:1000-1:2000 scale with 2-3km coverage, and construction drawing design at 1:500-1:1000 scale with 0.5-1km coverage.
Steel specification framework including structural steel, reinforcement, and specialized steel components with grade classifications.
Investigation of water level variations including tidal ranges and seasonal fluctuations affecting tunnel positioning and structural loads.

Intermediate phase investigation providing detailed site characterization for preliminary design development as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.3.3. Requires minimum 5 boreholes in complex geological areas with 100-300m spacing. General boreholes penetrate 1.5 tunnel height below base while control boreholes reach 2.5 tunnel height in soft soils.

Site construction condition data including site location, water and power supply systems, construction material sources, equipment accessibility, and machinery deployment requirements. Essential for construction planning, logistics optimization, and resource management as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.2.2.

Current status and planning data including road traffic, urban construction, port terminals, waterway transportation, and shoreline protection as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 4.2.2. Essential for comprehensive site assessment and regulatory compliance verification.
Plan design framework with centerline intersection requirements and alignment specifications for immersed element sections.
Design framework for immersion joints and connection segments ensuring optimal water level conditions and hydraulic pressure requirements.
Systematic investigation of subsurface soil and rock conditions including material properties, stratification, and engineering characteristics for foundation design.
Dry dock scheme determination based on investment, construction schedule, element count, site conditions, navigation, and hydrological factors.
Systematic framework encompassing all environmental aspects, site conditions, and ecological considerations for immersed tunnel engineering.
Design parameters derived from research data analysis for tunnel design consideration.
Location assessment meeting hydrological and navigational conditions while facilitating construction and environmental protection.
Layered visualization of soil and rock distribution for geological modeling.
Overall tunnel layout design meeting requirements for operation, maintenance, disaster prevention, and emergency rescue.
Topographic mapping for preliminary design with scale range 1:1000 to 1:2000 and coverage extending 2-3 km on both sides of tunnel alignment.
Design framework ensuring adequate protective cover over tunnel roof and positioning below scour line with special considerations for exposed conditions.
Parameters for waterproofing system design based on environmental conditions.

Alignment design ensuring tunnel centerline intersects navigation channel centerline and shoreline at a right angle or large angle as specified in GBT 51318-2019 Section 5.3.1. Critical for maintaining navigation safety and optimizing tunnel positioning relative to waterway infrastructure.
Geometric boundary conditions for tunnel alignment and trench design derived from topographic data.
Additional hydrological parameters relevant to tunnel design including temperature variations, salinity, and chemical composition affecting materials and construction.
Environmentally friendly and sustainable material selection.

Floating transportation distance determined per GBT 51318-2019 Section 10.2.5 using historical hydrological and meteorological data analysis (tide level, depth, velocity, gravity, wind speed, wave height). Distance calculated considering optimal floating time windows per Section 10.2.6: dry dock freeboard >100mm, visibility >1000m, flow velocity <1.0m/s, pipe towing velocity <1.0m/s, wave height <0.6m, wind speed <10m/s. Route planning utilizes existing navigation channels where possible per Section 10.1.3. Navigation channel requirements ensure minimum depth Ht >= H - hg + hs where H is external pipe height, hg is freeboard, hs is safety clearance. Value expressed in meters.
